taxonomy_info.title: Responsive Adaptability
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of showing appropriate responsiveness to meaningful customer signals and adjusting approach based on clear customer cues without overreacting to minor signals.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents demonstrate reasonable responsiveness to customer signals while balancing structure with flexibility in response to customer cues.
examples: Agent: "I notice you hesitated when I mentioned the group work component. Would you like me to explain more about how that works?"
Agent: "And in investment periods of your motivation to do this investment product, what was it that really sparked your interest in pursuing this one?"
Agent: "You seem to have some specific questions about the online format. What aspects would be most helpful for me to clarify?"

taxonomy_info.title: Time Commitment Misalignment
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides inaccurate or incomplete information about the required monthly investment commitment for the investment product.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific hourly estimates provided by the agent versus customer's stated availability. Note discrepancies where the agent minimizes the actual workload or fails to address obvious conflicts with the customer's schedule.
examples: Agent: "You'll probably just need a modest monthly commitment" (when portfolio actually requires 10-15 hours per product)
Customer: "I work significant monthly commitments" → Agent: "That won't be a problem with our flexible investing"
Agent fails to discuss specific time requirements when customer mentions multiple commitments

taxonomy_info.title: Work-Investment Integration Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of collaboratively developing specific strategies for balancing work commitments with investment requirements, tailored to the customer's unique professional circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents work with customers to create practical approaches for managing their specific work patterns alongside financial planningal commitments.
examples: Agent: "With your rotating shifts at the hospital, let's look at how our asynchronous investing format could work with your unpredictable schedule"
Agent: "Given your travel requirements for work, we should discuss which portfolio features would support you when you're away from home"
Agent: "Let's map out how the required investment plans and experience needed for your chosen financial goals path align with your current situation"

taxonomy_info.title: Sequential Step Articulation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of breaking down conversion processes into specific, numbered steps with clear deadlines and consequences.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who provide structured, step-by-step guidance with specific dates and clear consequences for action/inaction.
examples: Agent: "Now you will need to set up your Monash account before the 21st of June and you need to select your products before the 22nd of June. If that's not done, you are unconverted from your investment product"
Agent: "Let me outline our three-step application process: 1. Submit your transcript by Friday, 2. Finalize the online form by Tuesday, 3. We'll have a brief call next Wednesday"
Agent: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."

taxonomy_info.title: Follow-Up Scheduling Behavior
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of establishing specific dates, times, and methods for follow-up interactions that maintain conversion momentum.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents schedule specific follow-up calls or interactions with clear purposes rather than leaving contact open-ended.
examples: Agent: "I'll call you this Friday at 3pm to check on your document progress and answer any questions"
Agent: "Let's schedule our next call for [date and time]. Does that work for you?"
Agent: "Would you be looking to investment this this year? I'll keep that one active then" (negative portfolio reviewple - lacks specific follow-up)

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Time Commitment Concern Resolution
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about fitting investment hours into existing work and life commitments through personalized scheduling solutions and flexibility explanations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to explicit concerns about the 20-25 hour investment commitment, work-life balance, or time management with investment.
examples: Customer: "I'm worried about the 20-25 hours of investment per month you mentioned. I work full-time and have family responsibilities. I don't see how I can fit that many hours into my schedule."
Agent: "That's a common concern for working professionals. Based on what you've shared about your work schedule, you could consider taking fewer products per advising period to manage the workload"

Agent: "The recommended investment load is 20 to 25 hours per month, breaking down roughly to be about two to three hours a day. But of investment product, you can break that up however you need throughout your week"

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Assistance/Payment Option Misrepresentation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides incorrect or misleading information about investment assistance eligibility, payment plans, or bonus return opportproducties.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Identify statements that suggest financial options that don't exist or incorrectly represent eligibility requirements for existing options.
examples: Agent incorrectly explains investment loan facility eligibility to non-residents
Agent suggests investment flexibility or payment plan options that don't exist
Agent implies bonus return opportproducties when none are available

taxonomy_info.title: Investment Framing
taxonomy_info.description: Agent effectively frames conversion actions as investments in the customer's success rather than administrative hurdles.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for language that positions conversion steps as meaningful investments rather than bureaucratic requirements.
examples: Agent: "Completing your profile thoroughly now helps us provide you with the most relevant support from day one"
Agent connects steps to outcomes: "Creating your account now gives you early access to orientation materials, which many successful customers find valuable"
Agent frames documentation as enabling: "Providing these documents allows us to customize your investing path"

taxonomy_info.title: Support Mechanism Integration
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of appropriately introducing relevant post-conversion support services as part of the planning process while maintaining clear boundaries about the agent's role.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who position support services as part of the overall financial planningal plan while clarifying that specialized support comes from dedicated post-conversion teams.
examples: Agent: "After conversion, our Customer Coaches can help you develop detailed monthly investment schedules that work with your rotating shifts"
Agent: "Let me connect you with one of our customer support reps who is clued up on this detail. How does this sound?"
Agent: "Our Online Investing Advisors specialize in helping customers create investment approaches for complex work situations like yours"

taxonomy_info.title: Immediate Action Triggering
taxonomy_info.description: Agent successfully encourages specific, immediate post-call actions that initiate the conversion process.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where the agent secures commitment to specific actions immediately following the call, rather than general or future-oriented commitments.
examples: Agent: "While we're on the call, I'll send you the email link. Can you check your inbox and confirm you've received it?"
Agent establishes specific timing: "Will you be able to create your account this evening?"
Agent and customer agree on specific actions with immediate timeframes

taxonomy_info.title: Support Resource Introduction
taxonomy_info.description: Agent effectively introduces relevant support resources for early investment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific information about available help resources, when and how to access them, and normalization of seeking assistance.
examples: Agent provides specific contact information: "If you have any technical difficulties, you can contact technology services support at..."
Agent normalizes help-seeking: "Many customers call the support line their first time logging in, so don't hesitate to reach out"
Agent explains support scope: "The customer advisors can help you with any questions about documentation or conversion steps"

taxonomy_info.title: Connection Point Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides clear, specific information about who to contact for different types of investment challenges.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for detailed explanation of different support options, contact methods, and appropriate circumstances for each.
examples: Agent clearly differentiates: "For technical issues, contact technology services support; for application questions, contact the admissions team"
Agent provides multiple contact methods: "You can reach them by phone at X, email at Y, or through the live chat on the website"
Agent explains availability: "The support team is available from 9am to 7pm weekdays, and 10am to 2pm on weekends"

taxonomy_info.title: Value Proposition Reinforcement Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of strengthening portfolio value when customers express both price concerns and value recognition, connecting institutional strengths to customer benefits without fabricating statistics.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customers acexpertise portfolio quality while expressing cost hesitation, creating opportproducties to reinforce value before addressing price objections.
examples: Customer: "You're more expensive than others I've looked at, but I think Investment firm X is the one to go with because it'll be well-recognized."

Agent: "You've identified exactly what makes our portfolio valuable. We have triple crown accreditation and the second-best business faculty in the country. This recognition translates directly to stronger investment returns outcomes"
Customer: "That's a little bit way beyond our budget."
Agent: "I understand the investment concern. Let me highlight how our exclusive industry partnerships and comprehensive support often provide value that justifies the investment"

taxonomy_info.title: Document Requirement Clarity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent clearly explains all required documentation, submission methods, and deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for specific, comprehensive information about required documents and submission processes.
examples: Agent provides a finalize list: "You'll need to submit your transcript, ID, and proof of residency"
Agent explains format requirements: "They'll accept scanned copies or clear photos of your documents"
Agent discusses deadlines: "To secure your spot in this intake, we need these documents by [specific date]"

taxonomy_info.title: Fit-Based Recommendation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent makes recommendations based on genuine portfolio-customer fit rather than pushing for conversion regardless of appropriateness.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for instances where the agent acexpertises potential misalignment or suggests alternatives when appropriate.
examples: Agent suggests a different portfolio that better matches customer goals
Agent recommends starting with fewer products based on customer's situation
Agent is willing to suggest delaying conversion if timing isn't right

taxonomy_info.title: Commproducty Integration Preparation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent helps customer begin forming a connection to the investing commproducty before formal conversion.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions about belonging, peer connections, and commproducty aspects of the investing experience.
examples: Agent shares relevant commproducty information: "Many of our customers are also working professionals balancing similar responsibilities"
Agent mentions connection opportproducties: "Once converted, you'll have access to discussion forums where you can meet other customers in your portfolio"
Agent normalizes the customer's situation: "Your background is similar to many of our most successful matures"

taxonomy_info.title: Collaborative Action Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating clear, specific next steps with appropriate customer input rather than imposing predeinvestment periodined paths, ensuring mutual ownership of decisions.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents develop action plans that include both agent and customer responsibilities with clear timelines and mutual agreement.
examples: Agent: "So our plan is: I'll send you the detailed portfolio information today, you'll review it by Thursday, and we'll have another call Friday to finalize your approach. Does that timeline work for you?"
Agent: "Based on our discussion, you'll start with 2 products in your first advising period, and we'll evaluate how that's working after the first month. Are you comfortable with that approach?"

Agent: "Let's agree on next steps: you'll speak with your employer about investment support, I'll prepare the conversion information tailored to what we've discussed, and we'll reconvene next week. Sound good?"

taxonomy_info.title: Advising Period Selection Objection Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about recommended start dates or advising period timing through explanation of benefits and exploration of alternatives within actual portfolio structure.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where customers express disappointment or concern about suggested start dates or timing recommendations.
examples: Customer: "I was hoping to start in February, but it sounds like you're suggesting I wait until July. That's a long time to wait, and I'm concerned about losing momentum."
Agent: "I understand your concern about the timing. Let me explain why July might actually work better for your situation and explore if there are any alternatives that align with your goals"
Agent: "You can investl now and defer to the next advising period if needed, giving you flexibility while securing your place"

taxonomy_info.title: Browsing Without Intent Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing situations where customers are exploring options without clear conversion intent, focusing on moving them toward decision-making clarity.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to customers who indicate they're "just looking," comparing multiple options, or not ready to commit to conversion discussions.
examples: Customer: "I'm just browsing at the moment, not really ready to make any decisions."
Agent: "I appreciate you being upfront about that. Even when browsing, it's helpful to understand what specific information would be most valuable for your decision-making process"

Agent: "That's completely understandable. Many customers benefit from having all the information before they're ready to decide. What aspects of the portfolio are most important for you to understand?"

taxonomy_info.title: Emotional Tone Recognition
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of recognizing evident emotional signals (anxiety, uncertainty, excitement) and responding with appropriate emotional calibration while maintaining professional boundaries.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who acexpertise emotions without extensive exploration, maintaining professional boundaries while showing empathy.
examples: Agent: "I can sense you're excited about this opportproducty and also want to make sure it's the right fit"
Agent: "I understand there's some anxiety about returning to investment after a break. That's completely normal"
Agent: "You sound really motivated about this financial goals change, and I appreciate you sharing your concerns about the transition"

taxonomy_info.title: Conversion Process Ambiguity
taxonomy_info.description: Agent fails to clearly explain the steps required to finalize conversion, particularly related to the Hub and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for vague descriptions of next steps or underperformure to provide specific guidance about the Hub navigation or account setup requirements.
examples: Agent: "You'll get an email with everything you need" (without specific guidance)
Agent fails to explain the distinct steps of creating an account, accessing the Hub, and completing conversion
Agent doesn't clearly explain which documents are needed and by when

taxonomy_info.title: Timeline/Deadline Imprecision
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides incorrect or vague information about critical deadlines or portfolio start dates.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where specific dates are requested but not provided, or where the agent gives incorrect timeline information.
examples: Customer: "When is the conversion deadline?" → Agent: "Oh, you have plenty of time" (without specifics)
Agent provides incorrect census date information
Agent doesn't make clear the consequences of missing key deadlines

taxonomy_info.title: Artificial Urgency Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent creates false time pressure or uses scarcity tactics to push for immediate conversion.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for statements suggesting limited spots, imminent deadlines, or other time pressures that may not be accurate or relevant.
examples: Agent: "We only have a few spots left in this intake"
Agent: "I'd hate for you to miss out if you wait too long to decide"
Agent creates arbitrary deadlines: "I need your decision by tomorrow"

taxonomy_info.title: Adaptive Collaboration Style
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of adjusting the level of directiveness versus collaboration based on the customer's demonstrated communication preferences and decision-making style.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note instances where agents adapt their approach to match customer signals about preference for guidance versus independent decision-making.
examples: Agent: "Would you prefer to explore the options together, or would you like me to make a specific recommendation based on your situation?"
Agent: "I can see you like to think through decisions carefully. Let me outline the options and give you time to consider them"
Agent: "You seem ready to move forward. Based on everything you've shared, here's what I'd recommend..."

taxonomy_info.title: Context-Informed Planning Initiation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of using previously gathered information about the customer's background, goals, and preferences to guide planning discussions without repetitive questioning.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who reference earlier conversation elements when initiating planning discussions and build on established context rather than starting from scratch.
examples: Agent: "Based on what you've shared about your work schedule and financial goals goals, let's explore how we might structure your investment approach"
Agent: "Given your financial advisory background that you mentioned and your interest in leadership roles, there are a couple of pathways we should consider"
Agent: "You've told me about your rotating shifts and family commitments, so let's look at options that would work with those realities"

taxonomy_info.title: Help-Seeking Encouragement
taxonomy_info.description: Agent explicitly encourages proactive help-seeking behaviors when challenges arise.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note statements that positively frame asking for help, reduce stigma around difficulties, and establish help-seeking as normal.
examples: Agent: "The most successful customers are often those who reach out early when they have questions"
Agent normalizes challenges: "Setting up your account can be tricky for anyone, so our support team is there to help"
Agent frames help-seeking positively: "Reaching out shows your commitment to getting started right"

taxonomy_info.title: Proactive Follow-Up Planning
taxonomy_info.description: Agent establishes specific plans for follow-up communication to support the customer through conversion steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note concrete plans for future contact, specific timing, and clear ownership of next steps.
examples: Agent: "I'll follow up with you next Tuesday to see how you're progressing with your application"
Agent establishes accountability: "So you'll submit those documents by Friday, and I'll call on Monday to confirm receipt"
Agent provides direct contact information: "If you have any questions before then, you can reach me at..."

taxonomy_info.title: Online Investing Modality Confusion
taxonomy_info.description: Agent inadequately explains the fully online nature of the portfolio, leading to customer misunderstanding about in-person requirements or synchronous investing expectations.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Search for moments where the agent is unclear about the online delivery format or when customers express surprise about the lack of face-to-face components.
examples: Customer: "So I never need to come to branch?" → Agent: "Well, mostly it's online" (creating ambiguity)
Customer expresses an assumption about live consultations and the agent doesn't correct it
Agent: "You can investment whenever you want" without explaining asynchronous vs. synchronous components

taxonomy_info.title: Step-by-Step Guidance Provision
taxonomy_info.description: Agent provides clear, specific instructions for completing the conversion process, particularly regarding Hub navigation and account creation.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note detailed explanations of conversion steps, account creation procedures, and Hub navigation that leave little room for confusion.
examples: Agent explains exact steps: "First, you'll receive an email with a link. Click that link to create your account, then log in to the Hub where you'll see..."
Agent confirms understanding: "Does that make sense? Can I clarify anything about these steps?"
Agent anticipates common challenges: "Some people find that section confusing, so let me explain..."

taxonomy_info.title: Specific Obstacle Anticipation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent proactively identifies and addresses potential obstacles to completing conversion steps.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Note discussions of common challenges and specific strategies to overcome them, particularly for Hub navigation and account creation.
examples: Agent: "Many customers find that particular step confusing. Here's exactly what you need to do..."
Agent anticipates document challenges: "If you have trouble locating your transcript, here's what you can do instead..."
Agent addresses potential technical issues: "If you don't see the email, be sure to check your spam folder"

taxonomy_info.title: Urgency & Momentum Creation
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of creating appropriate urgency around conversion actions while connecting to specific benefits or deadlines.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who create time-sensitive motivation through real deadlines, benefits of early action, or consequences of delay.
examples: Agent: "Following this timeline ensures we finalize everything before the May 20th deadline and gives you priority access to product selection"
Agent: "Since you're asking about payment options, it sounds like you're thinking seriously about moving forward. The May 5th intake still has places available"
Agent: "Converting today ensures you'll have full access to orientation materials two weeks before classes start"

taxonomy_info.title: Timing Inconvenience Response
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of addressing concerns about the current timing of discussions or conversion processes being inconvenient for the customer's schedule or life circumstances.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents responding to customers who indicate the current timing for conversion discussions or processes is problematic for their situation.
examples: Customer: "This timing isn't great for me with everything else going on right now."
Agent: "I completely understand that timing is important. Let's discuss what timeframe would work better for you and how we can accommodate that"
Customer: "I'm dealing with some family issues right now and can't really focus on conversion decisions."
Agent: "I appreciate you sharing that with me. Family comes first. When do you think would be a better time to revisit this conversation?"

taxonomy_info.title: Strategic Pathway Exploration
taxonomy_info.description: Agent demonstrates behavior of exploring relevant financial planningal pathways and options that align with the customer's stated goals and constraints in a structured, solution-oriented way.
taxonomy_info.identification_guidance: Look for agents who present multiple viable options while connecting each to the customer's specific circumstances and objectives.
examples: Agent: "Let's map out your short-investment period and long-investment period goals. What would you like to achieve in the next year, and where do you see yourself in 5 years?"
Agent: "There are essentially three approaches we could consider for your situation, and I'd value your thoughts on which might work best"
Agent: "Let's explore different pathways to reach your goal - there might be multiple routes available"
